The USDA announced that flexibility has been granted regarding school meal programs. Districts are now allowed to continue the free meal program through the end of the calendar year.

post_text: Year book pick up for WVHS August 4 & 5
shared_text:
West Valley High School
July 27 at 5:36 PM ·

YEARBOOK DISTRIBUTION

The 2019-2020 West Valley yearbooks have arrived. Yearbooks will be distributed on Tuesday August 4th and Wednesday August 5th from 4:00 to 7:00 pm. Seniors will be allowed to pick up their yearbooks one hour early (only on Tuesday 8/4) at 3:00 pm. This is a drive up, pick up only. Students are to remain in their vehicles during this event. Due to Covid-19 guidelines, there will not be a signing even at this time.

Students who have prepaid for their yearbooks will proceed to the two pick up lines in the teacher parking lot on the Southeast side of the school. There are a limited number of unsold yearbooks and they will be sold on a first come first served basis. These yearbooks can be purchased by credit/debit card only at the tent in the South Parking Lot (Senior Lot).

Students who are not able to pick up on these dates can pick up their yearbook when school resumes in the fall.

post_text: Seth Woodard celebrates their PACE Character Student Of The Year.
shared_text:
Seth Woodard Elementary
June 5 at 4:31 PM ·

Seth student Rylee was recently awarded with the PACE Award! This is what Rylee's teacher has to say about Rylee's tremendous attributes!

The maturity and compassion that Rylee shows her classmates have had such an enormously positive impact on our learning environment! She participates in such a way that shows that it's okay to make mistakes and to be honest when we need help. She encourages others to participate and to be willing to share their mistakes, learning, and achievements. She encourages others to be themselves, listens to others when they need to be heard, and most importantly leads by example. She has a stronger self-assured confidence that I have seen in a 5th grade student and that kind of confidence builds people up. It has been wonderful to watch her grow and I can only imagine what she will grow up to achieve.

- Mrs. Daley

post_text:
WV students, parents and community....it's happening! WV will host a BE THE LIGHT event on Friday, April 17th to honor our Seniors and show our support for the Class of 2020! Our stadium lights will light up at 8:20pm. ✨

✔️ Please feel free to drive by but please respect social distancing and stay in your cars. Do not come on campus - simply drive by and honk your horn. Please practice safe driving and if you are home, know we are thinking of you and we will be posting pictures! Drive through the mapped area starting at 8:20pm. Please refer to the map below.
✔️ Use #bethelight or #WVHSbethelight for social media posts
✔️ Staff and coaches will be cheering from the sidewalks (6 ft apart) as students drive by. Anyone can drive through to cheer and honk and say hello!
✔️ All students, families and community members are welcome to drive by. Everyone is required to remain in their vehicle.
✔️ We will be out cheering for 20 minutes! The football stadium lights will come on at 8:20pm that will signal the start.

post_text:
School Board Directors accepted Deputy Superintendent Doug Matson's resignation at a recent board meeting. He will retire at the end of the school year. Doug spent his 31 year career in charge of West Valley's Finances and has become an expert on school budgets.
During his career Doug has received many awards and accolades and has served on many local and state boards. He is a two-time past president of the Washington Association of School Business Officials and a member of the State Accounting Advisory Committee, as well as the State Safety Net Committee for Special Education.

The district will reorganize the business office and will not hire a replacement superintendent.

Congratulations Doug, you will be missed!

The West Valley School Board Directors accepted the resignation of Dr. Gene Sementi during their board meeting December 11. Sementi will step down as Superintendent effective June 30, 2020. The board also voted unanimously to appoint current Assistant Superintendent Kyle Rydell as incoming Superintendent.
Dr. Sementi has been an integral part of the West Valley family for the past 31 years and will be sorely missed.

post_text:
Students and staff from Spokane Valley High School, Dishman Hills HIgh School, Centennial Middle School, Ness, Orchard Center, Seth Woodard and Pasadena Park Elementary schools participated in the annual ValleyFest Bedrace and Hearts of Gold Parade.
In all, there were more than 200 participants from seven West Valley schools. Congratulations to the team from Dishman HIlls High School who entered the bed race and won the Best Bed/Costume award. A student band from SVHS sat atop the school designed and created float entertaining the crowd with their music. A dance team followed performing dance routines down the parade route. Students from CMS and all four elementary schools walked the parade route to cheers from the crowd.

We are excited to announce the use of the BrightArrow Communications System to reach families and staff by phone, email and text message. If West Valley has a cell phone number for you in Skyward, you will receive a text message Thursday morning inviting you to opt-in for future text messages.
When you receive the initial text message, please follow the prompts to opt-in. You may wish to save this number to identify it as West Valley's communication phone number. If you do not receive a text message and want to opt-in for messaging, or you have questions about this new system, please email info@wvsd.org and leave your contact information. Prompt, accurate emergency and informational communication with you is very important to us so please be sure your Skyward contact information is correct.

The Spokane County Library District will use their All of Us Community Engagement Outreach Award grant dollars on a project that partners with Dishman Hills High School. The Fit & Lit: Health Literacy for Teens project will focus on supporting academic success and teaching better health. Activities will include specially created health and science classes, programs on how to identify quality health research, production of health related videos, and free YMCA memberships and bus passes for the summer of 2020.
Read the entire Spokane County Library publication about the program here at https://www.wvsd.org/apps/news/article/1075361

post_text:
Kyle Rydell recently joined the West Valley family as Assistant Superintendent. He is a graduate of EWU, earned his Masters at Gonzaga, his principal certification at EWU and his superintendent certificate at WSU.
Mr. Rydell began his teaching career in East Valley where he advanced to Assistant Principal and Athletic Director at East Valley Middle School before moving to Trent Elementary as Principal. After 14 years with East Valley he was hired as Superintendent in Republic and spent the past five years as Superintendent at Liberty School District.
Kyle was raised in the valley and he and his wife Laura have a college age daughter and a son who will be a WVHS Eagle in the fall. He has an open-door work style and looks forward to meeting the West Valley staff and getting to know the West Valley community.
We welcome the entire Rydell family to West Valley.

We welcome the entire Rydell family to West Valley.

post_text:
WVSD chose Wagstaff Inc. as their Community Leader of the Year and honored them at a recent Association of School Administrators luncheon. Wagstaff has been an active and supportive business partner with WVSD for many years.
Their commitment to education and students is poignant and extends regionally. Wagstaff employees serve in advisory roles for CTE programs, have mentored FIRST Robotics teams, and have supported many hands-on field trips and career-connected learning opportunities to every middle school in the Spokane Valley. They will also launch a summer program for high school students to gain experience working in the trades. We are grateful to Wagstaff for investing in the future of our students!

post_text:
The WVHS Robotics team wrapped up their season with a very impressive finish at the recent World Competition in Dallas. The 19-member Team 2147 (Chuck) competed against the top 400 teams from 40 countries.
The team was selected to the third place alliance with a team that works out of, and is mentored by, NASA/Johnson Space Center engineers and astronauts. Working with the highly resourced teams they won in the quarterfinals but lost to the eventual winners in the semi-final round by 3 points. Students also had the opportunity to experience several cultural activities while in Texas. Congratulations Team 2147 on another highly successful year

Mar 10, 2019 - Daylight Saving Time Starts
When local standard time is about to reach
Sunday, March 10, 2019, 2:00:00 am clocks are turned forward 1 hour to Sunday, March 10, 2019, 3:00:00 am local daylight time instead.

Sunrise and sunset will be about 1 hour later on Mar 10, 2019 than the day before. There will be more light in the evening.

WVHS Senior Xiang Yu (Vincent) Gao is one of only eight seniors to receive the YMCA of the Inland Northwest Most Promising Urban Leaders Scholarship. The full-tuition, full-need urban leadership award is worth up to $250,000 per student.

post_text: Congratulations to Outdoor Learning Center Director Jami Ostby Marsh who was granted $12,000 from the Hagan Foundation to fund the Project NEST program. She will work in partnership with the Hutton Settlement on Project NEST, which is a program to create a Nature Therapy Garden. The garden will provide spaces and activities that benefit children by improving communication, social skill development, sensory exploration, and expanding their comfort zones and routines.

post_text: Dishman Hills instructor Jason Abrams applied for a Hagan Foundation Grant to fund a Learning Through Music program. His application was funded and the school received $4,867. post_text: CMS instructors Kellie Marlow and Ashleigh Greule were presented the district Above and Beyond Award at a recent school board meeting. They were nominated for their "It starts with Hello" campaign. After attending a PACE workshop on Character Education, the duo reported back to Principal Karen Bromps with ideas for how the Centennial student body could participate in World Character Day, as well as further the school-wide Character Strong program. They created the "It starts with Hello" program for Character Day in September and the idea has continued on at the school. Congratulations to these dedicated Character Champions.

post_text: This time of year weather conditions may cause a change in the regular school day. We have a process in place to make weather related decisions about a delayed start or cancellation of the regular day. If this is necessary, we will activate our emergency telephone and text message system to notify families. Additional information about the inclement weather procedure can be found on our website at www.wvsd.org

post_text:
Investigators have identified the suspects involved in the social media threats made against local schools Tuesday. The Spokane Valley Police Department and Spokane County Sheriff's Office released a statement saying there is no imminent danger to students and staff related to these criminal threats. The incident remains under investigation.
Authorities also stated that as a reminder, parents should talk to their children about the use of social media and the need to immediately report threats without forwarding them to their friends. As always, the safety of our students and staff is our number one priority.

post_text:
Social Media Investigation
You may have heard there is a threat spreading on Social Media (Snapchat) directed at local high schools. We are actively investigating this at WVHS and believe it is related to the threat at East Valley. Our resource officer and security team are on site. School will continue as normal today. The safety of our students and staff is our number one priority.
